    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. but how does the body actually get rid of it though? like once i stop running, does it just sit there or is there a specific process to clear it out? is it a slow thing?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Once you stop running, your body starts to rid itself of the excess lactic acid through several mechanisms. One of the primary ways is through the removal of lactic acid by the bloodstream, which is then transported to the liver for processing. The liver converts lactic acid into glucose, which can be used by the body or stored for later use. This process is relatively quick, taking around 30-60 minutes. Additionally, your muscles also have a mechanism to reabsorb lactic acid from the bloodstream, known as the \"lactic acid shuttle\". This process is facilitated by a protein called alanine transaminase, which helps to neutralize the lactic acid and return it to the muscle cells for reuse.",
